    "headline": "Is ZA a Scrabble Word? Yes! 11 Points for This Pizza Slang",
    "description": "ZA is a valid Scrabble word in both TWL and SOWPODS. Worth 11 points, ZA is informal for pizza and the highest-scoring 2-letter Z word.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-23",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/is-za-a-scrabble-word" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is ZA a valid Scrabble word?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes! ZA is valid in both TWL (Tournament Word List) and SOWPODS (Collins Scrabble Words). It scores 11 points (Z=10, A=1) and is the highest-scoring 2-letter Z word available in Scrabble." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does ZA mean in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "ZA is an informal shortening of 'pizza.' It entered common American slang and was added to the Official Scrabble Players Dictionary in 2006. Despite its casual origin, it's fully legal in competitive tournament play." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What other 2-letter Z words exist in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "In TWL, ZA is the only 2-letter Z word. In SOWPODS (Collins), ZO (a Tibetan yak hybrid, 11pts) is also valid. ZE is valid in SOWPODS only as a gender-neutral pronoun. ZA remains the most universally accepted 2-letter Z play." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <span class="text-gray-300">Word Validity</span>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Is ZA a Scrabble Word? Yes! 11 Points for Pizza Slang</h1>

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-23">June 23, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>4 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Got that high-value Z tile but nowhere to put it? ZA is your answer. Worth 11 points for just two tiles, ZA is the informal shortening of "pizza" that every Scrabble player needs in their arsenal. Like its partner QI, ZA was added to the official dictionary in 2006 and immediately became one of the most strategically important 2-letter words in the game.
      </p>

      <!-- Hero Card -->
      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">🍕 Z-Tile MVP</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">ZA</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">11 points · Z(10) + A(1) · Informal: pizza · Added 2006</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">ZA is the most-played Z word in competitive Scrabble. Short for pizza, it gives you an easy outlet for the 10-point Z tile whenever an A is accessible on the board. Combined with premium squares, ZA regularly scores 20-30+ points in a single play.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Stat Strip -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">11</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Base Points</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">31</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">On Triple Letter</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">2006</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Year Added</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">#1</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">2-Letter Z Word</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Dictionary Validity</h2>

      <p>ZA is accepted in every major Scrabble dictionary. No matter where or how you play, ZA is legal.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Valid in TWL (NASPA)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Tournament Word List — all North American competitive play, NASPA-sanctioned tournaments and clubs</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Valid in SOWPODS (Collins)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Collins Scrabble Words — international tournaments, UK, Australia, and worldwide competitive play</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">What Does ZA Mean?</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">📖 Definition</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">ZA is <span class="text-white font-medium">informal slang for pizza</span>, commonly used in American English. The clipping became widespread in casual speech during the 1970s-80s, particularly among younger speakers. Example: "Let's grab some za after the game." While some purists objected to its inclusion in the Scrabble dictionary, its established usage in American English qualified it for official recognition.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Z-Tile Strategy with ZA</h2>

      <p>The Z tile is worth 10 points — the second-highest value after Q. ZA gives you a reliable way to deploy it without needing a complex setup.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Triple Letter targeting:</span> Z on a Triple Letter Square = 30 points for Z alone, making ZA a 31-point play. With A being the most common letter in the bag (9 tiles), opportunities arise frequently.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Parallel plays:</span> Play ZA alongside existing words to form multiple crosswords. Since A appears in countless 2-letter words (AA, AB, AD, AE, AG, AH, AI, AL, AM, AN, AR, AS, AT, AW, AX, AY), the A in ZA almost always creates a valid cross.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">ZAS plural hook:</span> ZA pluralizes to ZAS (12pts). If ZA is on the board, you can hook an S to score while building your main word through it.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Early Z deployment:</span> Unlike Q, don't hold the Z too long hoping for PIZZA or JAZZ. Playing ZA early on a premium square is often worth more than waiting for a longer Z word that may never come.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">2-Letter Z Words Comparison</h2>

      <p>How does ZA stack up against the other 2-letter Z options?</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">ZA — 11pts (TWL + SOWPODS)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Universal. Valid everywhere. Only needs an A tile — the most common letter in the bag. Your default Z-dump word.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">ZO — 11pts (SOWPODS only)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">A Tibetan yak hybrid. Valid in international/Collins play only — NOT valid in TWL/North American tournaments. Know your dictionary before playing.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">ZE — 11pts (SOWPODS only)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Gender-neutral pronoun. Collins-only — invalid in TWL. Risky play unless you're certain of the dictionary being used.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Related Articles -->
      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/is-qi-a-scrabble-word/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
